# IIfx A/UX 3.0.1 HD Boot — progress-pinning test.
#
# Drives the IIfx through the SCSI HD boot path.  On the SE/30 the boot
# blocks reach Mac OS, the Set-Startup application "A/UX Startup" auto-
# launches, "Welcome to A/UX. Loading..." paints, the kernel loads, the
# A/UX login screen appears, root logs in, and the Mac-on-A/UX desktop
# renders.
#
# HISTORY
# -------
# Earlier states pinned by this test (each replaced as the boot
# advanced):
#
# 1. Pre-iHSKEN-write fix (doc-81 §10C): IIfx stuck at Mac OS Finder
#    of MacPartition — A/UX Startup never even launched because the
#    iHSKEN-armed wrapper-write loop dropped its data.  Reference:
#    mac-finder.png (retained for archaeology).
#
# 2. Post-iHSKEN-write fix, pre-iHSKEN-command fix (doc-83): IIfx
#    reached "Welcome to A/UX. Launching..." but immediately kernel-
#    panicked "no root file system" because the iHSKEN COMMAND-phase
#    write path silently dropped the INQUIRY CDB.  Test would have
#    pinned a screenshot of the panic banner.
#
# 3. Post-iHSKEN-command fix + chip-side phase-transition fix
#    (doc-83 + CSR/BSR deferred-phase-transition): IIfx now passes the
#    SCSI INQUIRY probe, autoconfig populates disk_slots[0]=1, vfs_
#    mountroot succeeds (no panic), but the kernel idle-loops at
#    $0005489E after the mount — full /etc/init load not yet working.
#    Reference: launching.png (retained for archaeology).
#
# 4. Post-BSR_INT-latch fix (doc-84 §6+ work):
#    A/UX's scsiirq dispatch now sees BSR_INT set and routes to the
#    state-decode block instead of "ignoring bogus irq".  Kernel
#    issued multiple SDMA SCSI READs but mount-root fs-type probe
#    still failed — kernel printed "panic: no root file system".
#    Reference: no-root-fs-panic.png (retained for archaeology).
#
# 5. Post-continuation-offset fix (this session — TCR LBS bit set on
#    EOP, continuation-arm detection in IIfx wrapper, dma_write_armed
#    bypass for external bus-master writes, sDCTRL READ status bits):
#    fs_types[3] (UFS) probe SUCCEEDS — kernel reaches the REAL MOUNT
#    path at $10032C86 (= match_count > 0 path), completes the actual
#    mount via SCSI WRITES, then enters Mac OS ROM space at $40843xxx
#    bouncing in the ROM's interrupt dispatcher.  The boot framebuffer
#    is cleared to gray (kernel transitioning to user-mode console).
#    No A/UX text observed in low RAM up to 12 MB — kernel hasn't
#    loaded /etc/init yet.
#    Reference: post-mount-stuck.png (the current pin).
#
#    Note (2026-05-31): the on-disk post-mount-stuck.png was originally
#    an accidental reuse of launching.png (identical md5 with the
#    "Welcome to A/UX. Launching..." dialog).  Re-captured against the
#    chip-faithful + kernel-credit-shim SCSI DMA model on this branch
#    so the file content now matches the state-5 narrative above
#    (truly blank gray framebuffer, no dialog).  Boot has since
#    advanced through libc1_s exec-load, init fork, and MAE coming up,
#    stalling later on a "bad dir ino 15360" kernel printf — but by
#    that point the framebuffer is already cleared, so the pin still
#    matches.  See local/gs-docs/notes/iifx-debug/ for the full
#    handover.
#
# CURRENT EXPECTED STATE
# ----------------------
# Screen: blank gray (framebuffer cleared, no panic text, no login).
# Kernel reaches the actual UFS mount call, processes WRITES, then
# spins in IIfx ROM's interrupt dispatcher at $40843xxx with IPL 7.
# task.state field reads as $FFFF (likely MMU remap during user-mode
# transition).  Autoconfig still completed (same as previous states):
#   - disk_slots[0] = 1, type[0] = $00, probe_counter = 1
#
# When the next blocker is unblocked (likely a missing IRQ source or
# IOP handshake), this screenshot will stop matching and the test
# should be expanded to drive A/UX login.

# Pin the wall clock so screenshot comparisons are reproducible.
rtc.time = 2026-04-26T21:30:36

# ~2G cycles takes the IIfx through Mac OS boot, A/UX Startup launch,
# the A/UX kernel _start, autoconfig, vfs_mountroot's UFS probe
# (success), the actual mount via SCSI WRITES, and into the post-mount
# state where the kernel bounces in IIfx ROM's interrupt dispatcher.
scheduler.run 2000000000

assert ${machine.id == "iifx"} "machine.id != iifx"
assert ${rom.checksum == "4147DD77"} "rom.checksum != 4147DD77"

# Default IIfx slot table seats the same JMFB card the IIcx/IIx tests
# use; the panel is 640x480 at 1 bpp.
assert ${screen.width == 640} "screen.width != 640"
assert ${screen.height == 480} "screen.height != 480"

# Bitwise compare against the captured "post-mount-stuck" state — a
# blank gray framebuffer reached after the actual UFS mount completes
# and the kernel transitions toward user-mode.  When the next blocker
# is fixed this will stop matching and the test should be expanded.
screen.match post-mount-stuck.png

# By the post-mount-stuck state, the kernel is past the UFS-probe
# phase (multi-block SDMA SCSI READs succeeded, the actual mount
# call was made via SCSI WRITES).  The kernel-init data structures
# (probe_counter, disk_slots[], type[]) get overwritten or remapped
# by then — they were asserted at the earlier "no-root-fs-panic"
# pin but no longer carry their post-autoconfig values.  The
# screen.match above is sufficient evidence of progress.

# Diagnostic probe: succeeds when A/UX UNIX is alive (writes via the
# MAE CRP), fails-soft otherwise (logs and returns).  Today the kernel
# is past vfs_mountroot but hasn't reached user mode; this still
# reports "no user-mode CRP observed yet".  Kept as a forward-looking
# signal of "full A/UX boot".
mouse.move 100 100 "aux"

quit
